c forenames:  Spanish Jose, Elena, Carlos, Fernando, Jacinto, Mario, Agustin, Ana, Dulce, Emilio, Enrique, Eugenio.","Spanish and Portuguese: from <i>Sancho</i>, a popular medieval personal name, which is probably from Latin <i>Sanc(t)ius</i>, a derivative of <i>sanctus</i> ‘holy’. The personal name was borne by a 9th-century Christian martyr of Cordova."]},{"name":"Saenz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Raul, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Mario, Francisco, Pedro, Ricardo, Alfredo.","Spanish (<b>Sáenz</b>): variant of <b>Sánchez</b> (see   Sanchez  )."]},{"name":"Sanz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Ricardo, Juan, Luis, Enrique, Jaime, Armando, Ernesto, Francisco, Manuel, Miguel.","German: from a short form, <i>Sando</i>, of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>sand</i> ‘true’.","German: habitational name from a place called Sanz in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Marañón","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Spanish (<b>Marañón</b>): habitational name from a place called Marañón in Navarre, from <i>maraña</i> ‘thicket, brushwood’. This surname is also found in the Philippines."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Constanza","type":"FIRST",